1️⃣ Internal Architecture

Spring Data JPA sits on top of:

Spring Data → JPA → Hibernate → JDBC → DB

What happens when you call:
accountRepository.save(account);


Internally:

Spring Data creates proxy implementation of repository

Calls Hibernate EntityManager.persist()

Entity stored in Persistence Context (1st level cache)

SQL not executed immediately

SQL executed on flush / commit

2️⃣ Persistence Context (Most Important Concept)

Persistence Context = First Level Cache

Stores managed entities

Example:

Account a1 = repo.findById(1);
Account a2 = repo.findById(1);


Only 1 SQL query runs → second comes from cache.

Entity States
State	Meaning
Transient	New object, not saved
Managed	Attached to persistence context
Detached	Not tracked anymore
Removed	Marked for delete
3️⃣ Dirty Checking (Automatic Update)

Hibernate automatically detects changes:

@Transactional
public void updateBalance() {
    Account acc = repo.findById(1).get();
    acc.setBalance(5000);   // No save()
}


Hibernate compares old vs new → generates UPDATE.

This is called Dirty Checking.
Dirty Checking is a Hibernate/JPA feature where you don’t need to call save() or update() manually.
If an entity is loaded inside a transaction and modified, JPA automatically detects the change and updates the DB when the transaction commits.

How It Works (Step-by-Step)

Transaction starts.

Entity is fetched from DB → becomes Managed (Persistent state).

You change any field in the entity.

Hibernate compares original vs modified values (dirty check).

On flush/commit, Hibernate automatically runs UPDATE.

Example
Entity
@Entity
public class Account {

    @Id
    private Long id;

    private double balance;

    // getters & setters
}

Service (Dirty Checking in Action)
@Service
@RequiredArgsConstructor
public class AccountService {

    private final AccountRepository accountRepository;

    @Transactional
    public void deposit(Long accountId, double amount) {

        Account acc = accountRepository.findById(accountId)
                .orElseThrow(() -> new RuntimeException("Account not found"));

        // No save() call here
        acc.setBalance(acc.getBalance() + amount);

        // Hibernate detects change and updates automatically at commit
    }
}


SQL Generated Automatically

update account set balance=? where id=?

When Dirty Checking Happens

On Transaction Commit

On EntityManager.flush()

Before executing another query (sometimes)

Entity States (Important)
State	Meaning
Transient	New object, not in DB
Persistent (Managed)	Loaded inside transaction → Dirty Checking works
Detached	Outside transaction → Dirty Checking ❌
Removed	Marked for delete
Common Mistakes
1. No Transaction → No Dirty Checking
// ❌ Won't update DB
public void updateBalance() {
    Account acc = repo.findById(1L).get();
    acc.setBalance(5000);
}


✔ Fix:

@Transactional

2. Detached Entity → No Update

If entity is modified outside transaction, JPA won’t track it.

✔ Fix: Use @Transactional or merge().

3. ReadOnly Transaction
@Transactional(readOnly = true) // ❌ No dirty checking

Dirty Checking vs save()
Dirty Checking	save()
Automatic	Manual
Works only in transaction	Works anytime
Efficient (only changed fields)	May update all fields
Performance Tip

If updating many records in loop, disable dirty checking batching:

@PersistenceContext
private EntityManager em;

for (int i = 0; i < list.size(); i++) {
    list.get(i).setBalance(1000);

    if (i % 50 == 0) {
        em.flush();
        em.clear();
    }
}

