8️⃣ Batching (Performance Boost)
spring.jpa.properties.hibernate.jdbc.batch_size=50
spring.jpa.properties.hibernate.order_inserts=true
spring.jpa.properties.hibernate.order_updates=true


Improves:

Bulk insert

Bulk update

Kafka consumers saving DB
Batching = Group multiple SQL operations (INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE) into one DB round-trip instead of executing one-by-one.
This greatly improves performance for bulk operations.

Why Batching Matters

Without batching (1000 inserts):

INSERT 1 → DB call
INSERT 2 → DB call
...
INSERT 1000 → DB call


With batching (batch_size=50):

50 inserts → 1 DB call
50 inserts → 1 DB call
Total = 20 DB calls (instead of 1000)


Huge performance gain ⚡

Step 1 — Enable Hibernate Batching

application.properties

spring.jpa.properties.hibernate.jdbc.batch_size=50
spring.jpa.properties.hibernate.order_inserts=true
spring.jpa.properties.hibernate.order_updates=true
spring.jpa.properties.hibernate.batch_versioned_data=true
spring.jpa.show-sql=true

Step 2 — Batch Insert Example
@Transactional
public void saveBulk(List<Account> accounts) {
    for (int i = 0; i < accounts.size(); i++) {
        accountRepository.save(accounts.get(i));

        if (i % 50 == 0) {   // batch size
            entityManager.flush();
            entityManager.clear();
        }
    }
}

Why flush() and clear()?
Method	Purpose
flush()	Sends batch to DB
clear()	Frees memory (avoids OutOfMemory for huge data)
Step 3 — Batch Update Example
@Transactional
public void updateBalances(List<Account> accounts) {
    int i = 0;
    for (Account acc : accounts) {
        acc.setBalance(acc.getBalance() + 100);

        if (++i % 50 == 0) {
            entityManager.flush();
            entityManager.clear();
        }
    }
}


Dirty checking + batching = ⚡ fast updates

Important: ID Generation Strategy

Batching does NOT work properly with:

@GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY) ❌


Use:

@GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.SEQUENCE) ✅


Because IDENTITY forces immediate insert → breaks batching.

MySQL Optimization (Very Important)

If using MySQL, add:

spring.datasource.url=jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/db?rewriteBatchedStatements=true


Without this → MySQL may ignore batching.

Insert vs saveAll()
accountRepository.saveAll(list);


✔ Works, but does NOT guarantee batching unless Hibernate batch settings enabled.

Best practice → Manual loop + flush/clear.

Batch Delete Example
@Transactional
public void deleteInBatch(List<Account> list) {
    accountRepository.deleteAllInBatch(list);
}


Efficient single query delete.

Memory Problem Without Batching

If inserting 1 lakh records without clear():

Hibernate keeps all entities in persistence context

Memory grows → OutOfMemoryError ❌

Batching fixes this.

How to Verify Batching Works

Enable SQL logs:

logging.level.org.hibernate.SQL=DEBUG
logging.level.org.hibernate.type.descriptor.sql=TRACE


You should see:

batching 50 statements

Performance Comparison
Records	Without Batching	With Batching
1,000	~4–6 sec	~0.5 sec
10,000	~40 sec	~4 sec
100,000	❌ May crash	✅ Works
