First Level vs Second Level Cache — Hibernate / JPA

Caching reduces DB hits → huge performance boost ⚡
Hibernate has 2 main cache levels:

Cache	Scope	Default
First Level Cache (L1)	Session / Persistence Context	✅ Enabled
Second Level Cache (L2)	Across Sessions / Application	❌ Disabled
1️⃣ First Level Cache (L1) — Session Cache
What is it?

Cache inside Hibernate Session / EntityManager

Stores entities during one transaction

Automatically enabled (cannot disable)

How it works
Account a1 = entityManager.find(Account.class, 1);
Account a2 = entityManager.find(Account.class, 1);


DB Hit?

First call → ✅ DB

Second call → ❌ From cache

Because same entity already in Persistence Context.

L1 Cache Lifecycle

Created when:

Transaction / Session starts


Destroyed when:

Session closed OR entityManager.clear()

Force DB Query (Bypass L1)
entityManager.clear();   // clears cache

Account a = entityManager.find(Account.class, 1);  // DB hit again

Important Behavior
Operation	L1 Cache Role
find()	Checks cache first
update()	Updates cache + DB
delete()	Removes from cache
flush()	Sync cache → DB
2️⃣ Second Level Cache (L2) — Application Cache
What is it?

Cache shared across multiple sessions

Stores entities globally

Disabled by default → must enable manually

Flow
Request 1 → DB → L2 Cache store
Request 2 → L2 Cache → No DB hit


Huge performance gain for read-heavy apps.

Step — Enable Second Level Cache
Add Dependency (Ehcache)
<dependency>
    <groupId>org.hibernate.orm</groupId>
    <artifactId>hibernate-jcache</artifactId>
</dependency>

<dependency>
    <groupId>org.ehcache</groupId>
    <artifactId>ehcache</artifactId>
</dependency>

application.properties
spring.jpa.properties.hibernate.cache.use_second_level_cache=true
spring.jpa.properties.hibernate.cache.region.factory_class=org.hibernate.cache.jcache.JCacheRegionFactory
spring.jpa.properties.hibernate.cache.use_query_cache=true

Enable Cache on Entity
@Entity
@Cacheable
@org.hibernate.annotations.Cache(
    usage = CacheConcurrencyStrategy.READ_WRITE
)
public class Account {
    @Id
    private Long id;
}

Cache Concurrency Strategies
Strategy	Use Case
READ_ONLY	Static data (countries, config)
READ_WRITE	Normal read/write
NONSTRICT_READ_WRITE	Slight stale allowed
TRANSACTIONAL	Strong consistency (rare)
L1 vs L2 — Key Differences
Feature	First Level Cache	Second Level Cache
Scope	Session	Application
Default	Enabled	Disabled
Shared?	❌ No	✅ Yes
Lifetime	Until session ends	Until cache expires
Config needed	❌ No	✅ Yes
Speed	Fast	Faster
Use case	Transaction-level	Repeated reads
Query Cache (Extra)

Caches query result, not entity.

Enable:

spring.jpa.properties.hibernate.cache.use_query_cache=true


Use:

Query query = entityManager.createQuery("from Account");
query.setHint("org.hibernate.cacheable", true);

Cache Eviction (Clear Cache)
Clear L1
entityManager.clear();

Clear L2
entityManager.getEntityManagerFactory()
             .getCache()
             .evictAll();

